subSubSection.paragraph:
Prothorax about 2/5 wider than long; coarse and dense sexually dimorphic punctation; surface with aspect alveolate, feebly demarcated (
Fig. 131
). Antemedian tubercle visible and elevated, smaller than postmedian, postmedian tubercle at right angle to axis of body. Pronotum with sexually dimorphic punctation concentrated principally in anterior and lateral region, absent on posterior region, transverse carina, median and postmedian elevations, anterior and posterior depressions and fine median longitudinal band in anterior region; elevations may possess coarse and sparse punctures. Sexually dimorphic punctation of pronotum with indentations shallow, rounded and ovoid (
Fig. 132
), denser and elongated at lateral region; each indentation with a single or with a several distinct cluster of pores (
Fig. 133
), distributed in all indentation; between indentations are scattered pores that may possess a short seta which is generally at apex (
Fig. 134
). Prosternal sulcus with dense, long and whitish hairs. Prosternal process smooth elevated and slightly narrowed at middle, at most 1/3 as broad as the procoxal cavity. Mesosternal process, at most subequal as broad as mesocoxal cavity; with discrete projection directed anteriorly; posterior margin sinuous.

Terminalia: Tergite VIII (
Fig. 140
) with apical margin adorned with yellow hairs. Sternite VIII (
Fig. 139
) transverse, apical margin emarginated and with long hairs at side and decreasing in length to middle which is glabrous; sternal apophysis about half as long as sternite. Ventral arc (
Fig. 141
) with short apophysis, about 1/10 as long as arms. Dorsal arc (
Fig. 142
) “U” shaped; apical margin with some sparse hairs. Tegmen (
Figs 143–145
) ¼ shorter than median lobe; distal region divided into parameres, which are cylindrical-elongate, narrowed to apex and with long hairs; ring piece elongated, fused at apex, with short apical projection. Median lobe (
Figs 146–148
): dorsal lobe slightly shorter than ventral lobe; apex of dorsal lobe rounded and ventral lobe acuminate; basal apophysis ⅓ longer than apical region. Internal sac with sclerotized piece “C” shaped.

Terminalia: Tergite VIII (
Fig. 149
) with apical margin sinuous. Posterior region of sternite VIII (
Figs 135–138
) two times wider than long; with a row of aciculate setae as long as conchoidal setae, conchoidal and petiolate setae longer and curved at apex, conchoidal setae with surface moderately wavy and with some slits; petiolate setae with dorsal slits; sternal apophysis about 2/5 longer than posterior region. Ovipositor (
Figs 150–151
) with short and parallel lateral lobes, margin with long, fine and sparse hairs, inner margin straight near vulva.
